So Johnny Appleseed wound up owning over a thousand acres. He paid people to tend them and they would sell—SELL—apple trees to locals from the orchards.

Basically the man set up Johnny Appleseed Franchises.

Well, you can’t EAT most wild apples, but it turns out you can still make hard cider.

Yeah, so it turns out that the dude was setting up orchards for hooch.

So back to Johnny Appleseed, who was roaming the frontier planting apple seeds that would grow into trees with almost entirely inedible fruit.

Ah…hmm.

So why does he get remembered with such affection?

The reason we have so many tasty apples and more than one Granny Smith tree is because of grafting. Basically you take a nice hardy apple tree that has great roots and inedible fruit, you jam a branch of Granny Smith onto it, and that branch grows Granny Smiths forever more.

The vast majority of wild apples, as it happens, are nearly inedible. Most of those genes are still present. So if you plant fifty apple seeds, the odds of any of them being edible are—look, get a mathematician for this. Suffice to say, Very Low.
